article.description: Tina Thompson scored 21 of her 33 points in the first half as the Houston Comets ended a five-game losing streak with a 97-61 win over the Detroit Shock on Thursday night.
article.headline: Comets end five-game skid
article.linkText: Thompson goes for 33 as Comets rout Shock
article.story:
HOUSTON (AP) -- Tina Thompson helped the Houston Comets put an
end to the worst losing streak in franchise history.

Thompson scored 21 of her 33 points in the first half as the
Comets ended a five-game skid with a 97-61 win over the Detroit
Shock on Thursday night.

Thompson, playing in just her third game since returning from a
calf injury, made 12 of her 20 shots and added six rebounds in the
Comets' first win since June 27 against Washington. Sheila Lambert
added a season-high 19 points for Houston, which avenged an 82-63
loss at Detroit on July 6.

"I just think we were a little tired, tired of losing,"
Thompson said. "Tonight was just a great example of us just being
ourselves. This is the kind of game that I think we needed so that
we can get out of whatever funk we were in. Hopefully we can just
continue to play at this level."

The Comets set their season high in scoring without Sheryl
Swoopes, who dressed but did not play while nursing a sore right
ankle. She is day to day.

"I thought it was a combination of us playing through five
straight losses and coming home to play the defending champions,"
Lambert said. "It feels good. Everybody played together and we
shot the ball with a lot of confidence. It always feels good when
you play like that."

Deanna Nolan scored 16 points for the defending WNBA champions,
who have lost two straight and fell to 8-9.

The Shock committed a season-high 26 turnovers and fell to 0-5
in Houston. The Comets lead the series 10-1.

"We got beat. There is no question about that," said Detroit
coach Bill Laimbeer. "We knew this was going to happen. They had
lost five in a row and they wanted this game more than we did.
There were no surprises. We knew how hard they were going to
play."

With the win, the Comets climbed into fourth place in the
Western Conference standings.

Houston shot 54.5 percent from the floor in the first half and
held a 49-30 lead at the half.

Thompson made eight of her 12 shots and led all scorers with 21
points in the opening half.

"We played hard tonight," said Comets coach Van Chancellor.
"That was the best team defense that we've played in a long time.
We got the ball from one side of the court to the other instead of
just holding the ball and standing around. When you back yourself
into a hole like we have, you just have to make plays."

After Detroit got within 13-10 on a layup by Swin Cash, Houston
used an 11-0 run to break open the game. Felicia Ragland hit a pair
of 3-pointers during the run and finished with nine first-half
points. Ruth Riley and Nolan each had eight points for the Shock
and Cheryl Ford had seven rebounds in the first half.
